Author: William Hendricks (hendrickswi)
Date: 03/13/26
Sprint 3
File(s) being reviewed: ChaseEnemy.cs, ProjectileEnemy.cs
Author of file: Ethan Chitturi (CoolestToDoIt)

Comments: 
  1) Memory leak in SetWeapon(IWeapon weapon). You subscribe to the 
    OnProjectileFired event for a weapon, but if the weapon ever changes
    during runtime, you never unsubscribe from the old weapon's 
    OnProjectileFired event.

  2) Violation of DRY (Don't repeat yourself) principle. The ChaseEnemy.cs
    and ProjectileEnemy.cs files are very similar (e.g., the properties,
    Update(), Draw(), RegisterMovement(), OnCollision() methods).

  3) You never actually use RegisterAttack(). 

  4) The overloaded OnCollision(IPlayer player) in ProjectileEnemy.cs is
    hardcoded to do one (1) damage to the player.

  Overall, the refactored enemy states are more reusable than ever. 
  We will be able to spawn enemies with the same behavior but different 
  sprites, and so forth. However, It also is quite a step up in 
  functionality from Sprint 2. It also has quite loose coupling with its
  use of mostly primitive properties. 

Suggested Changes: 
  1) Could handle it by doing something like this: 

      public void SetWeapon(IWeapon weapon)
      {
          if (weapon == null) return;
          if (Weapon != null)
          {
              Weapon.OnProjectileFired -= HandleProjectileFired; 
          }
      
          Weapon = weapon;
          Weapon.OnProjectileFired += HandleProjectileFired;
      }

      // Extract the lambda into an actual method so you can unsubscribe from it
      private void HandleProjectileFired(IProjectile proj)
      {
          OnProjectileCreated?.Invoke(proj);
      }

  2) Extract most logic into an EnemyBase abstract class and override 
    methods as needed. This will also allow you to implement new enemy 
    behaviors (e.g., FlyingEnemy, etc.) way easier. I did something 
    similar with BaseWeapon.cs and BaseProjectile.cs, if you're 
    interested.

  3) You could have the OnCollision(IPlayer player) method call 
    RegisterAttack(), then RegisterAttack() would call 
    CurrentState.HandleAttack() and transition the enemy into the 
    attack state if in a valid state to do so (i.e., idle, moving).

  4) You actually already have a ContactDamage property in this file. 
    You can just do player.TakeDamage((int)ContactDamage). You can 
    fix this alongside suggested change 2). 
